doc.after: American paddlefish are highly mobile and well adapted to living in rivers.[5] They inhabit many types of riverine habitats throughout much of the Mississippi Valley and adjacent Gulf slope drainages. They occur most frequently in deeper, low current areas such as side channels, oxbows, backwater lakes, bayous, and tailwaters below dams. They have been observed to move more than 2,000Â mi (3,200Â km) in a river system.[5]
